{"title_page": "Thouqan Hindawi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name=Thouqan Hindawi\n|office2=President of the Royal Hashemite Court\n|image=Thouqan_Hindawi.jpg\n|termstart1=1993\n|termstart2=1989\n|office1=Deputy Prime Minister of Jordan\n|resting_place=The Royal Tombs of the Hashemite, Al-Maquar\n|honorific-prefix=[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1927|6|23}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|2005|7|2|1927|6|23}}\n|death_place=[[Amman, Jordan]]\n|parents=Salem Hindawi {{small|(father)}}\n|termend2=1995\n|termend1=1995\n|nationality=[[Jordan]]ian\n|monarch1=[[King Hussein]]|monarch2=[[King Hussein]]|country1=Jordan|primeminister1=[[Abdelsalam al-Majali]]|primeminister2=[[Mudar Badran]]\n[[Zaid ibn Shaker]]|birth_place=[[Irbid, Jordan]]|birth_name=Thouqan Hindawi}}\n\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (12).jpg|thumb|His Excellency Thouqan Hindawi Deputy Prime Minister & Minister of Education 1994 Amman]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (8).jpg|thumb|Chief of The Royal Hashemite Court ]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (13).jpg|thumb|Elected Deputy Thouqan Hindawi 1990]]\n'''Thouqan Hindawi''' was born in 1927 in The Hindawi Madafa or Court of his father Sheikh Salem Basha Hindawi in the Northern Region of The Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan which was [[Emirate of Transjordan]] at that time. During his life, Hindawi served for over 40 years in several key government positions from 1965 until 2005. Some of these positions include Chief of [[The Royal Hashemite Court]], [[Deputy Prime Minister]], [[Minister of Education]], Minister of Finance, Minister of Social Affairs, Minister of Labor, [[Minister of State]] for Prime Ministry Affairs, Senator, and Ambassador. Hindawi died in 2 July 2005 and was buried in The Royal Cemetery inside The [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]] near the tomb of  King [[Hussein of Jordan]].\n\n== Education ==\nThouqan Hindawi started his schooling in the Northern Region of Jordan then at a later stage joined [[Arab College (Jerusalem)|Arab College]] in Jerusalem in 1943 as well as  [[University of London]] in 1945 in which made him earn by 1947 his Palestinian Secondary School Certificate.  Hindawi earned in 1950 his [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] Degree in History from [[Cairo University]] and in 1956 his [[Master's degree]] in Advanced Education from [[University of Maryland]].<ref>https://archive.org/stream/JordanTimes1991JordanEnglish/Nov%2023%201991%2C%20Jordan%20Times%2C%20%234862%2C%20Jordan%20%28en%29_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n== Occupation ==\n[[File:Thouqan with king.jpg|left|thumb|King Hussein & Thouqan Hindawi]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (7).jpg|alt=Hindawi's First Ministerial Post as Minister of Media with Wasi Al Tal in 1965|thumb|Hindawi's First Ministerial Post as Minister of Media with Wasi Al Tal in 1965]]\n\nAfter earning his [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] Degree, Thuqan Hindawi started his career in the Public Sector in 1950 as History Teacher in the Ministry of Education in Jordan. Soon after that he was promoted to become an Education Inspector and then the Director of the Teacher's Training Academy of Beit Hanina.\n\nHindawi moved in 1962 to become Director of Social Affairs at [[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unrwa.org/|title=UNRWA {{!}} United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|website=UNRWA|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> He remained until he was appointed as Educational Attach\u00e9 in the Jordanian Embassy in Cairo <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17161/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Cairo, Egypt|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> in 1964 and as the General Secretary of the Ministry of Media in Jordan at that same year.\n\nHindawi held his first Ministerial Position with Prime Minister [[Wasfi al-Tal]] in 13 Feb 1965 as the Minister of Media. After that he continuously held many key Ministerial Cabinet Positions in Jordan from 1965 until 1995 including [[Deputy Prime Minister]], [[Minister of Education]], Minister of Finance, Minister of Social Affairs, Minister of Labor, and [[Minister of State]] for Prime Ministry Affairs.\n\nHindawi was also chosen by the late King [[Hussein of Jordan]] to be [[Chairman|Chief]] of [[The Royal Hashemite Court]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |title=The Royal Hashemite Court |url=http://www.rhc.jo |journal=Main Website |language=en}}</ref> Ambassador,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordanembassy.org.au/|title=Home|website=www.jordanembassy.org.au|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17523/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Kuwait City, Kuwait|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and Senator in the Upper House of Parliament. He was also elected in the Jordanian Public Elections of 1989 as a Deputy in the Lower House of Parliament for a 4 year term.\n\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (6).jpg|thumb|With His Majesty The King 1966]]\nMost of his life, Hindawi was on the Board of Trustees of a number of government and private academic institutions including the [[University of Jordan]] and [[Yarmouk University]] as well as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Applied Science University and Arab Community College. \n\nHindawi received several prestigious State Medals and International Awards from a variety of Countries and Organizations. He wrote and published the Palestinian Case book which was consistently taught in the Jordanian Secondary Curriculum from 1967 until 1994.    \n\nHindawi remained publicly active as well as in Government Positions until he suddenly died on 2 July 2005 and was buried in in The Royal Cemetery inside [[The Royal Hashemite Court]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unofficialroyalty.com/royal-burial-sites/jordanian-royal-burial-sites/|title=Jordanian Royal Burial Sites|website=Unofficial Royalty|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> near King [[Hussein of Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kinghussein.gov.jo/biography.html|title=Biography - His Majesty King Hussein bin Talal|website=www.kinghussein.gov.jo|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.pm.gov.jo/arabic/index.php?page_type=news&part=1&id=890\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hindawi, Thouqan}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name=Thouqan Hindawi\n|office2=President of the Royal Hashemite Court\n|image=Thouqan_Hindawi.jpg\n|termstart1=1993\n|termstart2=1989\n|office1=Deputy Prime Minister of Jordan\n|resting_place=The Royal Tombs of the Hashemite, Al-Maquar\n|honorific-prefix=[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1927|6|23}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|2005|7|2|1927|6|23}}\n|death_place=[[Amman, Jordan]]\n|parents=Salem Hindawi {{small|(father)}}\n|termend2=1995\n|termend1=1995\n|nationality=[[Jordan]]ian\n|monarch1=[[King Hussein]]|monarch2=[[King Hussein]]|country1=Jordan|primeminister1=[[Abdelsalam al-Majali]]|primeminister2=[[Mudar Badran]]\n[[Zaid ibn Shaker]]|birth_place=[[Irbid, Jordan]]|birth_name=Thouqan Hindawi}}\n\n\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (12).jpg|thumb|His Excellency Thouqan Hindawi Deputy Prime Minister & Minister of Education 1994 Amman]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (8).jpg|thumb|Chief of The Royal Hashemite Court ]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (13).jpg|thumb|Elected Deputy Thouqan Hindawi 1990]]\n'''Thouqan Hindawi''' was born in 1927 in The Hindawi Madafa or Court of his father Sheikh Salem Basha Hindawi in the Northern Region of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan which was The [[Emirate of Transjordan]] at that time. During his life, Hindawi served in several key government positions from 1965 until 2005. Some of these positions include Chief of [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]], Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Finance, Minister of Education, Senator, and Ambassador. Hindawi died in 2 July 2005 and was buried in the cemetery of The [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]].\n\n== Education ==\nThouqan Hindawi joined  [[Arab College (Jerusalem)|Arab College]] in Jerusalem in 1943 as well as  [[University of London]] in 1945 in order to earn by 1947 his  Palestinian Secondary School Certificate.  Hindawi earned  in 1950 a [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] Degree in History from [[Cairo University]]  and in 1956 a [[Master's degree]] in Advanced Education from [[University of Maryland]].<ref>https://archive.org/stream/JordanTimes1991JordanEnglish/Nov%2023%201991%2C%20Jordan%20Times%2C%20%234862%2C%20Jordan%20%28en%29_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n== Occupation ==\n[[File:Thouqan with king.jpg|left|thumb|King Hussein & Thouqan Hindawi]]\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (7).jpg|alt=Hindawi's First Ministerial Post as Minister of Media with Wasi Al Tal in 1965|thumb|Hindawi's First Ministerial Post as Minister of Media with Wasi Al Tal in 1965]]\n\nHindawi started his career in 1950 as a History Teacher in the Ministry of Education in Jordan. He was promoted to become an Education Inspector and then as the Director of the Teacher's Training Academy of Beit Hanina in 1956. Hindawi became In 1962 Director of the Department of Social Affairs at the [[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unrwa.org/|title=UNRWA {{!}} United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|website=UNRWA|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> He was appointed as the Educational Attache in the Jordanian Embassy in Cairo <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17161/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Cairo, Egypt|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> in 1964 until he was appointed as the General Secretary of the Ministry of Media and Government Communications in The Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan in that same year.\n\nHindawi held his first Ministerial Post with Premier [[Wasfi al-Tal]] in 13 Feb 1965 as the Minister of Media.\n\nHindawi held after that a number of Ministerial Positions from 1965 until 1995 including [[Deputy Prime Minister]], [[Minister of Education]], Minister of Finance, Minister of Social Affairs, Minister of Labor, [[Minister of State]] for Prime Ministry Affairs. Hindawi also was chosen to be the [[Chairman|Chief]] of [[The Royal Hashemite Court]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |title=The Royal Hashemite Court |url=http://www.rhc.jo |journal=Main Website |language=en}}</ref> Ambassador of Jordan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordanembassy.org.au/|title=Home|website=www.jordanembassy.org.au|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17523/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Kuwait City, Kuwait|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and Senator. Hindawi was elected as a Deputy in 1990 for a 4 Year Term.\n\n[[File:Thouqan Hindawi (6).jpg|thumb|With His Majesty The King 1966]]\nHe was on the Board of Trustees of the [[University of Jordan]], [[Yarmouk University]], and Chairman of the Board of the Arab Community College. Hindawi received for his work several prestigious State Medals as well as international awards from a variety of Countries and Organizations.\n\nHe held many positions until he died on 2 July 2005 and was buried in in The Cemetery of [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unofficialroyalty.com/royal-burial-sites/jordanian-royal-burial-sites/|title=Jordanian Royal Burial Sites|website=Unofficial Royalty|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> near [[Hussein of Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kinghussein.gov.jo/biography.html|title=Biography - His Majesty King Hussein bin Talal|website=www.kinghussein.gov.jo|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://ww